Commit Message: Changed license to a less restrictive (public domain, no copyright)
pip travis does not install distutils packages
Added links to Ruby and Elixir ports to README.md ) fix #15 fix #16

Allow static min and max via cfg

Sometimes auto-scale is just not what you want, you can now just say cfg['minimum'] = 0 and cfg['maximum'] = 100 and the scale stays fixed.
Added a Docstring to __init__.py, to make the use of cfg parameters more intuitive.
avoid dividing by zero & handle single value

Improve pplot - expose all options, better docs.

All of the configuration options can now be passed from the script; the defaults are still used correctly if any options aren't given. I've also added a couple of help strings where I thought of a concise message.
change readme to markdown in setup.py

Clean up Python code.

This removes a handful of unnecessary uses of `abs`, `float`, and `int` and also puts in a check to ensure that the maximum value for the plot is greater than the minimum value. No functionality is changed here.

Add Rust port

Added Rust port reference to ports section
added a link to PHP port

Fix position of initial point on y-axis

In the Python version of asciichart, the position of the first tick mark
is sometimes drawn incorrectly due to a rounding error. The value should
be `round` up, but the `int` function is used instead.

Before the change (the tick mark on the y-axis is at 4.5, but it
should be at 6.25):

    > python3 ./pplot --height 3 6 1 8
    >     8.00  ┼
    >     6.25  ┤╮╭
    >     4.50  ┼││
    >     2.75  ┤││
    >     1.00  ┤╰╯

After the change:

    > python3 ./pplot --height 3 6 1 8
    >     8.00  ┼
    >     6.25  ┼╮╭
    >     4.50  ┤││
    >     2.75  ┤││
    >     1.00  ┤╰╯

Add support for NaNs and fix min/max behavior

Data series may now contain NaNs. NaN values will insert a space
in the chart to indicate missing data:

    >>> series = [1,2,3,4,float("nan"),4,3,2,1]
    >>> print(asciichartpy.plot(series))
    4.00  ┤  ╭╴╶╮
    3.00  ┤ ╭╯  ╰╮
    2.00  ┤╭╯    ╰╮
    1.00  ┼╯      ╰

Fix a bug if data values exceeded user-defined minimum and maximum
values. The prior version failed to clamp the values, so the following
would not be possible:

    >>> series = [1,2,3,4,float("nan"),4,3,2,1]
    >>> print(asciichartpy.plot(series, {'minimum': 2, 'maximum': 3}))
    3.00  ┤ ╭─╴╶─╮
    2.00  ┼─╯    ╰─

Improve the API documentation by adding a module docstring as well as
adding several examples to the plot docstring.

Rename _isan to _isnum for clarity

I was tryng to keep with the existing math.isnan, but _isan is too
vague, so I changed it to _isnum instead. In the ideal world, this
function wouldn't even be needed if the project did not support python
verions less than 3.2 (where math.isfinite was introduced).

Add support for multiple series in Python version
Checking for int() doesn't accomodate other types such as float(), instead check that series is not a list()
Fix mistake which always set the minimum to 0 even when a minimum was presnet in cfg. This was breaking Travis build checks. Also added docstring test for Travis to protect multi data series support

Specify y-axis min/max hints

This is for cases when the chart needs a y-axis min smaller than, or a max larger than, the bounds of the series.

For example, it's quite common to want the chart to have a 0 value on the y-axis, regardless of the data. Also being able to specify the max gives the caller a chance to create a range that has 'sensible' rounded tick values on the y-axis.

Also add some test coverage

Changed the default behaviour to print no colour symbols instead of the 'reset' colour
